One Labour MP voiced concerns about his grouping, saying the new name rhymes with the Welsh words “twp” and “pwp”.
For readers outside Wales: in Welsh the word “twp” means stupid, and the word “pwp” means waste.
One of Plaid Cymru's politicians said his group was "unsatisfied" with the proposal and presented other solutions.
A member of the Welsh Conservative Party said his party was "open" to changing its name, but noted that the word "MWP" was very similar to the word "muppet".
In this case, the Welsh letter "w" is pronounced similarly to the letter "u" in the English Yorkshire dialect.
The committee working in the Assembly, which is currently working on a draft law to change the name, took the following position: "Of course, the final decision on the future title of the members of the Assembly will be their own".
The Government of Wales Act 2017 gave the Welsh National Assembly the right to change its name.
In June, the committee published the results of the public consultation on the proposal, and the re-appointment of the assembly to the Welsh Parliament was widely supported.
In addition, the committee supported the proposal to change the title of members of the assembly to "Member of the Welsh Parliament", i.e. WMP in English, although the abbreviation "MWP" enjoyed the greatest popularity among the public.
The members of the assembly are proposing alternative solutions. The difficulties of reaching a consensus are a hardship for Elin Jones, the speaker of the assembly, who is expected to present the bill in the coming weeks.
The law introducing the reforms will also take into account other changes in the way the Assembly works, including the rules for recalling members and the structure of the committee system.
Members of the National Assembly will be able to vote on their future title during the discussion of the bill.
