John Edward: language skills necessary for the citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland are constantly enjoying their scientific achievements – in 2018 they were able to boast of another excellent exam results, supported by individual and collective successes in sport, art, music and other social endeavors.
Represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), schools attended by more than 30,000 students across Scotland strive to provide the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, the career paths chosen by them and to indicate their role as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that has the opportunity to develop and implement a curriculum tailored to the needs of the school, we see that modern languages are still popular and desirable subjects to choose from in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to another person in a language that they understand, it goes to their head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart.”
It’s a clear reminder that we can’t just rely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The results of the last exam this year show that languages occupy the first place in league rankings, with the highest scores occurring in the case of independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of the students who learned foreign languages received a higher grade A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students received a higher grade A in Mandarin, and 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students, and 63 percent of Spanish students also received an A grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, learning languages as subjects to choose from is conducted in the same scope as learning STEM subjects (strict sciences, technology, engineering, and mathematics) as part of teaching programs in independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills (UK Commission for Employment and Skills) found that 17 per cent of employers reported a lack of language skills in their candidates due to difficulties in filling vacancies.
Therefore, more and more language skills are becoming a necessity to prepare young people to start a professional career.
These skills are essential in a globalised world with a growing number of jobs requiring language skills.
A lifelong skill, like learning a second language, will provide a huge advantage in the future — no matter what career path you take.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically increases the chances of a multilingual person in relation to the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults, 75% of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language with a two-digit percentage of those using it, i.e. 15%.
That’s why investing in foreign language learning is so important for today’s children.
Knowledge of several languages, in particular the languages of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a suitable job.
In Scotland, each school will be different in terms of the languages it teaches.
Many schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will be teaching languages deemed most important to the UK in the 2020 perspective, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the child’s interests, there will always be many languages to choose from in independent schools, which will be taught by teaching staff specialized in this area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed — no matter what the future holds for them.
At present, it cannot be denied that in an international business environment, languages are still crucial to the future of the country, and so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be treated as ‘international communication skills’.
Independent schools will continue to offer Scottish youth a wide choice, diversity and level.
It's just the right thing to do.
John Edward, President of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
