While Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s reluctance to renege on a “gradual” approach to denuclearization, under which North Korea would be rewarded for taking gradual action, his statement appeared to be significant, as he did not renege on a single point of view.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between the U.S. security chief and North Korea’s leader, which took place in Singapore on June 12, when Kim Jong Un pledged to work for “denuclearization and denuclearization” of Trump.
North Korea had expected a formal end to the Korean War (between 1950 and 1953), but the U.S. delegation announced that Pyongyang must first give up nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls for the easing of harsh international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, even opposing the signing of a ‘declaration of an end to the war,’” Ri said.
“The conviction that sanctions can bring us to our knees is the grudges of people who behave ignorantly towards us.
