Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest.
The new course at Harvard University, which took place this year, provided all students with more sleep, which was aimed at combating the growing macho culture of learning by “all-night caffeine-powered students.”
Academic students from the best university in the world often have no idea about the basics of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course that he says is the first of its kind in the United States.
To create the course, he was inspired by a speech on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
At the end of the speech, a girl came up to me and said, “Why am I being told this only now that I’m in my final year of college?”
She stated that no one ever told her about the meaning of the dream, which surprised me,” the Telegraph said.
The course, which was held for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep-related habits help achieve good results in science and sport, as well as improve the overall well-being of students.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health service, said that this course was decided to be introduced after it was found that students suffered from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The hourly course includes a number of interactive tasks.
One section includes a picture of the dorm room where students click on coffee cups, curtains, exercises, and books to get information about the effects of caffeine and light, and how sleep deprivation affects athletic performance, as well as how important it is to maintain sleep regularity.
In another section, participants learn how a long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
“We know that this will not cause an immediate change in the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as everyone has a right to know what the health effects of smoking cigarettes are,” added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in “all-night science” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students means a growing problem of lack of sleep.
Ensuring a sufficient amount of good quality sleep should be a student’s “secret weapon” to fight stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, and even to avoid gaining weight because lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, making the student constantly hungry, he said.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop a course after taking part in one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push for the introduction of a course for the entire campus.
The next step according to him is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before moving on to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set an alarm to remind them when to go to sleep and when to get up, as well as to be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by the screens of electronic devices and LED lighting, which can distort the circadian rhythm and lead to problems with sleep.
