A new cancer vaccine could teach the immune system to "detect" enemy cells and destroy them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize hostile cells as part of treatment.
This method consists of separating the immune cells from the patient and changing them in the laboratory.
Then they can "see" the protein common to many cancers. Then they are injected back into the body.
The trial vaccine shows promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
In one woman treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize hostile cells, ovarian cancer has been reported to disappear for more than 18 months.
The method consists in separating immune cells from the patient, changing them in the laboratory so that they can “detect” a protein common to many cancers called HER2, and then injecting those cells back into the patient.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results indicate that the vaccine is doing very well.
HER2 “drives the growth of several types of cancers,” including breast, ovarian, lung, and colon cancers, Prof. Berzofsky explained.
A similar approach of taking immune cells from patients and “teaching” them to locate cancer cells worked in the treatment of a certain type of leukemia.
