The National Trust is eavesdropping on the secret life of bats
New research carried out on the property in the Scottish Highlands aims to show how bats use the landscape when gaining food.
The results of the studies are expected to shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future action to protect them.
The study, conducted by researchers from the National Trust for Scotland, will target common and small dwarfs, as well as long-eared brown bats and bats from the red-night family at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
In key locations around the property, special recorders will be deployed to keep track of bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out field research using portable detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings is aimed at determining the frequency of signals sent by bats and the way in which individual species behave.
Then a habitat map and report will be developed to create a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor at NTS, hopes the findings will reveal which habitat areas are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows, as well as the best ways to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
The populations of bats in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are at risk from construction and development works that have an impact on the fences and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can also pose a threat, as can fly adhesives and some chemicals used in building materials, and even domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more helpful than their eyes in catching prey.
They use a complex echolocation technique to search for worms and obstacles on their way.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It consists of ten trained experts who regularly conduct examinations, checks of the herd, and sometimes even rescue actions.
The organisation has even established Scotland’s first and only dedicated bat reserve on the Threeve estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
David Thompson, the estate manager, says it is the perfect territory for bats.
“Threave has a great area for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and great settlements.
However, there are still many unknowns when it comes to bats. The work we do here and in other estates will help us better understand what they need to develop."
He stresses the importance of controls for the presence of bats before embarking on maintenance work on the estates, since unintentional destruction of one rod can kill up to 400 females and young, which can lead to the disappearance of the entire local population.
Bats are under protection—killing, harassing, or disturbing them, as well as destroying their nests is illegal.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer at the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to help.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and in many species we don’t even know how their populations are doing.”
