Nancy Pelosi calls Brett Kavanaugh a “hysterical” and says he’s not fit to work in the Supreme Court
House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi called Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh a “hysterical” and said he was by nature unfit to work in the Supreme Court.
Pelosi made the remarks during an interview she gave Saturday at the Texas Tribune Festival in Austin.
“I think that if a woman behaved this way, she would be considered ‘hysterical,’” Pelosi said of her reaction to the testimony Kavanaugh made to the Senate Judiciary Committee on Thursday.
Kavanaugh emotionally denied the allegations of alleged sexual harassment of Dr. Christina Blasey Ford when they were both teenagers.
For moments during his pre-speech speech, Kavanaugh showed strong emotions — he almost screamed and lost his speech when discussing family matters and high school years.
He also clearly chastised Democrats on the committee, calling the charges against him a "grotesque and coordinated attack on reputation" organized by liberals angry that Hillary Clinton lost the 2016 presidential election.
Pelosi said Kavanaugh's testimony showed he was not fit to serve on the Supreme Court because it revealed his bias against the Democrats.
“I think he disqualified himself by making these statements, as well as by the way he attacked the Clintons and the Democrats,” she said.
Asked if she would seek Kavanaugh’s removal from office if he received the nomination and if the Democrats won a majority in the House of Representatives, Pelosi hesitated.
“If he doesn’t tell the truth to Congress or the FBI, he should not only sit on the Supreme Court, but also serve in the court where he currently works,” she said.
Kavanaugh is currently a judge in the District Court of Appeals in the District of Columbia.
Pelosi added that as a Democrat she fears Kavanaugh's possible rulings on the Affordable Care Act or the Roe v. Wade trial because he is considered a conservative judge.
During the hearing, Kavanaugh evaded questions about whether he would overturn some of the Supreme Court’s rulings.
"This is not the time to bring a hysterical, prejudiced person into court who will expect us to say 'it's wonderful,'" Pelosi said.
