What benefits can the economic war between the United States and China bring to Beijing?
The salvos that started the economic war between the US and China were deafening and although the battle is still ongoing, in the long run, the conflict between these countries may be beneficial to Beijing, experts say.
The first warning this year was fired by U.S. President Donald Trump, imposing tariffs on key Chinese exports, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation came this week after the introduction of new tariffs on $200 billion (<0xC2><0xA3>150 billion) worth of goods, which resulted in the taxation of half of all goods coming into the U.S. from China.
Each time Beijing reciprocated in nature, recently raising tariffs on US goods worth $60 billion from five to ten percent.
China is determined to respond to any U.S. strike, and it doesn’t look like the world’s second-largest economy is about to give up.
Forcing Washington to withdraw means accepting demands, but publicly bowing one’s head to the United States would be too embarrassing for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
According to experts, however, if Beijing plays its cards well, the pressure from the US trade war could strengthen China in the long run, reducing the ties between the two economies.
“The fact that a quick political decision taken in Washington or Beijing could create the conditions for unleashing economic chaos in any of the countries is actually much more dangerous than what observers have previously conceded,” said Abigail Grace, an American think tank researcher at the New Security Center.
Foreign Minister Says Syria Is 'Ready' to Repatriate Refugees
The government says Syria is ready for the voluntary return of refugees, and is asking for help in rebuilding a country devastated by more than seven years of war.
In his speech to the UN General Assembly, Syrian Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that conditions in the country are improving.
“The situation on our territory is now more stable and secure thanks to progress in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
In an effort to restore normalcy, the government is constantly rebuilding areas destroyed by terrorists.
All the conditions have already been met so that refugees who have had to leave the country because of terrorism and unilateral economic moves aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods can voluntarily return to it.
According to UN estimates, since the beginning of the war in 2011, more than 5.5 million people have left Syria.
Another six million people who still live there need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be happy to accept help in rebuilding the destroyed country.
He stressed, however, that he would not accept aid protected by conditions or offered by countries that sponsored the rebellion.
Europe secures victory in the Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team won the 2018 Ryder Cup, beating the U.S. team 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National in the suburbs of Paris.
On European soil, the United States has lost for the sixth time in a row and has not won the Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained the trophy when, under the leadership of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn, it scored 14.5 points, which were needed to defeat the US.
The American star, Phil Mickelson, who did not fare well through most of the tournament, hit the ball from the base straight into the water at the 16th hole of PAR3, giving the match to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari shined through all the rounds and became one of four players who, since 1979, when this tournament was held for the first time in the current format, managed to get a score of 5-0-0.
American Jordan Spieth was eliminated 5&4 by the lowest ranked player from Europe, Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark.
Dustin Johnson, who holds the highest position in the world ranking, lost two holes to Ian Poulter, for whom it may have been the last Ryder Cup tournament.
